author: Amazon Customer
date: Reviewed in the United States on October 19, 2021
content: I'm not sure why so many people struggled with the assembly. While it wasn't something I was used to, the pieces were labeled and the pictures were easy to follow. I was nervous at first to put any pressure on the pieces to get them into place, but it worked out fine. I'd suggest looking closely at the pictures and making sure you have everything lined up properly before committing, because I'd imagine this would be near impossible to get back apart.For all pieces but the lid, I was able to just gently apply pressure after getting the pieces lined up. For the lid, I simply laid it out like the pictures showed and pressed gently with my foot to lock it into place.At the end of the day, it feels a little flimsy to me and I wish it were sturdier feeling. I do like that the lid holds itself up so that I can easily pack items in and remove them. I ordered a cover to help with the water resistance, because I don't expect that this will be very waterproof.At the end of the day, this box is going to work for me, but I wish I would have paid a little less for what it is (If it had been sturdier so that someone could sit on it, for example - I'd be very happy).

author: Amazon Customer
date: Reviewed in the United States on October 19, 2021
content: I'm not sure why so many people struggled with the assembly. While it wasn't something I was used to, the pieces were labeled and the pictures were easy to follow. I was nervous at first to put any pressure on the pieces to get them into place, but it worked out fine. I'd suggest looking closely at the pictures and making sure you have everything lined up properly before committing, because I'd imagine this would be near impossible to get back apart.For all pieces but the lid, I was able to just gently apply pressure after getting the pieces lined up. For the lid, I simply laid it out like the pictures showed and pressed gently with my foot to lock it into place.At the end of the day, it feels a little flimsy to me and I wish it were sturdier feeling. I do like that the lid holds itself up so that I can easily pack items in and remove them. I ordered a cover to help with the water resistance, because I don't expect that this will be very waterproof.At the end of the day, this box is going to work for me, but I wish I would have paid a little less for what it is (If it had been sturdier so that someone could sit on it, for example - I'd be very happy).

author: Amazon Customer
date: Reviewed in the United States on October 19, 2021
content: I'm not sure why so many people struggled with the assembly. While it wasn't something I was used to, the pieces were labeled and the pictures were easy to follow. I was nervous at first to put any pressure on the pieces to get them into place, but it worked out fine. I'd suggest looking closely at the pictures and making sure you have everything lined up properly before committing, because I'd imagine this would be near impossible to get back apart.For all pieces but the lid, I was able to just gently apply pressure after getting the pieces lined up. For the lid, I simply laid it out like the pictures showed and pressed gently with my foot to lock it into place.At the end of the day, it feels a little flimsy to me and I wish it were sturdier feeling. I do like that the lid holds itself up so that I can easily pack items in and remove them. I ordered a cover to help with the water resistance, because I don't expect that this will be very waterproof.At the end of the day, this box is going to work for me, but I wish I would have paid a little less for what it is (If it had been sturdier so that someone could sit on it, for example - I'd be very happy).

content: I just finished putting the box together and noted a few things that could be clearer in the description. 1) The item description says waterproof but when you read deeper it says water-resistent. author: Shoeless
date: Reviewed in the United States on September 22, 2022
content: The assembly instructions (Just a set of illustrations, no words) make only the slightest mention that the base of the unit is asymmetrical. (The notches on the sides of the base are not equal.)  If you fail to note the small "a <= b" in the illustration and assemble the unit it will not go together correctly.  Once the sides have snapped together there is no way to disassemble them to fix your error.  I bought two units and now one of them is trash because I assembled it wrong.The units come with a card offering product support but NONE is available.  If you call the phone number listed a recording will tell you they're either on the line with another customer or you've called after hours. I've called at various times over the course of several days but all I get is that recorded message. They do allow you to leave a message and they promise to call you back but don't hold your breath!  I've left a couple of messages but haven't received a call yet.Bottom line: Don't buy anything from this manufacturer unless you are perfect at interpreting illustrated instructions!

author: Amazon Customer
date: Reviewed in the United States on October 20, 2022
content: I have nothing but good with these so far. We got them during the summer and they held up being in sunlight all the time. We’ve had a few rainy days and everything has stayed dry inside. We us one for pool toys and the other for equipment and furniture cover storage. They are a little dirty in my photos but look just as good as outta the box. If you can read instructions they are overly simple to put together. Just take your time.UPDATE.I still love these boxes and think they are great. They still look good after 1 year in the California sun and have kept water out. However there may be some quality control issues. I ordered a 3rd large box to fill with more useless stuff for the pool. When the 3rd box arrived and I was putting it together I noticed that the strut arm assembly didn't sit well nor did the lid close like the others. I say this to say that the lid didn't close all the way when it was put together (in comparison to the lids on the other boxes). So I put my detective hat on and started to inspect the boxes for any differences. I found that the old boxes had the area where the screws go sticking out away from the side panel about 1/4 inch +/-. This space allows the hinges clearance to freely open and close (my 4th photo). The new box had this area flush with the side panel causing the issue of the strut arms not sitting well and the lid closing funny (5th photo). It ended up being a simple fix. I added a small plastic spacer and a new screw (6th photo) to have it sit where it should. All in all the boxes are well built and serve the intended purpose well but I dropped 1 star to reflect the defect found. I actually have a 4th box that is same style yet smaller size for another area in the yard. 1 small issue in 4 boxes isn't bad but I'm quite handy and saw this as a minor inconvenience. Another customer who might lack some DIY skills would be frustrated with spending the money for these and putting them together, only to find out they have an issue. I've read other reviews that state that you cannot return them once they are together. Once they snap into place the box can't be taken apart without breaking something. I'd still recommend them however pay close attention to my photos as well as other customers photos so that you can inspect them prior to putting them together. I hope that the company takes this information and provides a disclaimer in the box to look out for certain things prior to putting together. This is more of a defect rather than damage but the only way you would know it is once it was put together. Hope this review helps others who buy this item know what to be on the look out for, before putting it together.

I added a small plastic spacer and a new screw (6th photo) to have it sit where it should. All in all the boxes are well built and serve the intended purpose well but I dropped 1 star to reflect the defect found. I actually have a 4th box that is same style yet smaller size for another area in the yard. 1 small issue in 4 boxes isn't bad but I'm quite handy and saw this as a minor inconvenience. Another customer who might lack some DIY skills would be frustrated with spending the money for these and putting them together, only to find out they have an issue. I've read other reviews that state that you cannot return them once they are together. Once they snap into place the box can't be taken apart without breaking something. I'd still recommend them however pay close attention to my photos as well as other customers photos so that you can inspect them prior to putting them together. I hope that the company takes this information and provides a disclaimer in the box to look out for certain things prior to putting together. This is more of a defect rather than damage but the only way you would know it is once it was put together. Hope this review helps others who buy this item know what to be on the look out for, before putting it together.

author: Mary Frank
date: Reviewed in the United States on December 30, 2023
content: This bench is nice-looking and it has good storage capacity. But other aspects have made me dissatisfied with this purchase.The assembly instructions are primarily illustrations with very few words. So many questions arose during assembly for which there was no help in the instructions. It took several hours to put together and it was a really frustrating process.The plastic it's made of doesn't seem very sturdy. During assembly, we used a rubber mallet to help join parts--as directed in the instructions. But still, the plastic split along a seam as a result of being hammered with the mallet.  In addition, when we raise the lid holding by on to just one end, the plastic warps and bends down at the other end, and then, when closed, the locking mechanism doesn't line up.Another note: the design of the lid makes it hold rain water and snow melt. The lid has multiple grooves in it, but no way to drain the water that collects in those grooves. We open the lid after rain and snow to brush water off of it. I'm concerned that if water freezes in those grooves, the flimsy plastic will crack.

author: Placeholder

content: I really like this box, and it's very sturdy, however it is not white.  My deck is white trimmed and I was trying to match it. This is a very light gray, as you can see from the picture.I'm giving it four stars due to the coloring being off.Also, I have a eight piece sectional that has cushions. They do not come close to fitting. My cushions are about 25 inch square and they are too tall to close the box. No matter which way I turn it, they are too tall. So we ended up just using the box for yard tools. That's my fault for not measuring before buying it. Definitely do your measuring.Update: So we've had this thing about 6 months and as I opened it up for spring to start getting stuff out, I realized that we had squirrels or something living in it. There's no hole, so I'm assuming they're getting in from under the flap. It does not seal closed like I would like it to. As you can see from the picture, the right hand side is sticking up. It's still pretty waterproof just because the top is kinda mushroomed over the sides so the water drips off, but I'm not as happy with it as I thought I would be.

author: Emary
date: Reviewed in the United States on June 3, 2023
content: Very disappointed - with all of the great reviews, I expected a well-made product with fairly easy assembly. That's not what we got. The deck box parts are very sturdy and the hardware is high quality; however, the assembly is very difficult. We were unable to assemble it completely because it is impossible to attach the side panels to the bottom panel no matter what we tried or how we muscled it. Using a rubber mallet as suggested in the instructions didn't help.We've put together a lot of furniture over the years, like IKEA for example, so it's not a lack of experience that's the problem. The instructions that come with the deck box don't state when to attach the support bars to the side panels. The big problem is if you put the end pieces on without the support bars, it's impossible to disassemble and reassemble again. Without the support bars and without the ability to snap the side tabs into the bottom panel, all you have is a floppy deck box that won't hold together.I've contacted the seller and will update this review oif the issue is solved.

author: Deb427
date: Reviewed in the United States on June 14, 2023
content: I’m a satisfied recent owner of the largest YITAHOME outdoor deck storage, but I was extremely disappointed and, frankly, embarrassed when I recommended this product to a family member and they went with the smaller 120 size.  The quality of the product and ease of set up is not the same.  The instruction manual for any size of this product needs improvement, but the installation help videos posted by others are extremely helpful (you just have to find them).  The pieces of the smaller size are not only flimsy and easy to crack but would not stay together in-spite of more than one attempt.  The amount of hardware for the smaller unit is a lot (39 screws alone) whereas the larger unit requires very few pieces.  And although it took less than a half hour to put together the largest unit, after spending an hour trying to get the sidewalls onto the smaller unit base, we were frustrated and left it for another morning.  Upon the second attempt, the sidewalls would not stay on the base.  As a consumer who had back-to-back experiences with set up of both sizes, please do not waste your time or money on the smaller unit.

author: J.
date: Reviewed in the United States on August 13, 2023
content: The product overall is fine, though I would not venture to sit on it.  Maybe it would bear the weight of a small child.  But the main reason for my rating is because the instructions were horrible.  The written portions were in 5 different languages and it was obvious the writer didn’t actually speak any of them.  Each instruction was maybe one sentence and accompanied by a picture that barely showed what to do in the step.  Putting it together was about an hour due to puzzling out what exactly to do.  As a hint, do NOT overtighten the screws.  They get inserted into plastic and there is minimal bite so the risk of stripping is high.  Also, make sure you insert the horizontal box reinforcing rods after you put on the first side wall but before you attach the second one.  Taking the box apart significantly increases the risk of breaking it completely due to how the joins work.

The media could not be loaded.
                



Relatively easy to put together, a rubber mallet is your best friend, and don't be afraid to use some umph to lock things in place. It's necessary. At first I was very impressed, and it is a very large size. It's attractive looking and I was able to sit on it. But after only about a month of light use out of nowhere all three bolts on one side just came out! The hinge popped out and I can't get it back in, and I have no idea how all this happened.  This has made me lose some confidence in this product. A compromised lid compromises the items inside. My best guess is weather, we've had a lot of wind and changes in temperature.  If after I fix it it starts to give me confidence back I will update my review.

author: GV
date: Reviewed in the United States on June 15, 2024
content: Ordered this box and it was delivered in excellent condition.  The assembly instructions leave a LOT to your common sense.  The pictures are not clear and the brief, multi-language written instructions with each picture are not easy to understand.  (Yes, my husband and I are both college graduates.)  During assembly, we had an issue understanding the instructions and I contacted the company directly - not through Amazon.  The person I was text-chatting with didn't know the answer, but I got an email within 24 hours with the best solution and we were able to complete assembly.Box is sturdy, strong, comfortable to sit on, looks great and works wonderfully for storing our deck stuff.  We've only had it out a few days, so i can't attest to the weatherproof claims.  It hasn't rained yet!The only reason I gave it only 4 stars instead of 5 is due to the difficult-to-understand assembly instructions.

author: Lanna
date: Reviewed in the United States on July 29, 2023
content: I had a problem with package carriers (including a carrier that rhymes with Blamazon) blatantly leaving boxes out in the rain despite having an overhang on my patio. The last straw was my order of bamboo toilet paper getting absolutely soaked, so I ordered this. Small enough to fit on my tiny patio, keeps the rain out as long as carriers bother to use it...My complaint is in the fact that it seems to be made with a cellulose material which attracts booklice like no tomorrow. Maybe this is the case with all deck boxes now as everyone wants to be better to the environment, but I'd gladly take good old fashioned resin in order not to attract thousands of tiny white mites. Thankfully they are harmless and not destructive so it's more of a nuisance than anything, but I still brush my packages off before bringing them inside just in case.Spraying the box periodically with bifenthrin does keep them at bay but I don't know if that will eventually degrade the material. Regardless, it was a very decent price when I bought so even if I only get a year or two out of it that is fine with me. Overall it's been a great addition to my tiny patio and I'm pleased with how it's working.

author: George Francis
date: Reviewed in the United States on June 19, 2023
content: When I received the item, no reason to suspect damage as the packaging was intact. Once I started putting it together and got to the lid, I noticed that the right rear corner was cracked on the top. Since this was turned upside down until I needed to add to the assembly, I did not see until that moment. I then sent a message to the vendor explaining the problem and if they could simply send out a replacement lid. They said that wasn't an option but stated that I could return the item for a refund or full exchange, which is perfectly fine. They also offered me a solution to refund me 25% of the purchase price. Since the damage did not affect the operation or compromise the waterproof aspect, we opted for the refund credit. The refund was immediate, the response from the customer service reps with Yitahome was quick and always within 24hrs of the previous message. You learn a lot from a company on how the resolve issues and I learned in this case that I would definitely put my faith in this company for future purchases.

content: I have very limited space where I needed to put this storage box for my grilling supplies, so this box is perfect. content: Looking at other reviews, I agree it isn’t too sturdy. My Ketor deck box is stronger, but this was the size I needed. author: SarahReadsALot
date: Reviewed in the United States on March 18, 2024
content: I love this box and my husband especially loves it. We live in a townhome and the only thing I dream of in having a bigger house is a mud room. My daughter and I ride horses (the reason we can't afford a bigger house lol!) and I come home with muddy boots. If I leave them outside the fox gets them or they get rained on. If we leave them inside we dirty up the house. This box is the perfect solution! It lives outside by our door, looks nice enough, and when we get home we just toss the dirty boots in there. So far no fox has swiped our shoes and they've stayed dry through several days of rain. It's perfect! My favorite amazon purchase of the year so far.Assembly was quick and easy. I read people's negative reviews about this and was very diligent. It definitely took some muscle to snap the parts into place and I made sure I did it right the first time because once it snaps in, it's IN. The box honestly doesn't feel heavy duty, but it's perfect for our use.

author: C. Radda
date: Reviewed in the United States on February 23, 2023
content: First off, this is not a piece of junk. It's sturdy and looks durable. The only thing I couldn't do with it was assemble it. And that's kind of important.The directions are laughable, especially the part that mentions a few taps with a rubber mallet. Most of the pieces are curved--good luck with that mallet. The eight curved sections constitute the barrel side, and you assemble four at a time. You'll get the hang of that after a few are done. Then you have two semi-circles. Assembling one side is fairly straightforward, but then you slide the base into the slots at the bottom, and everything ends. Hours of trying to connect the final two sections were fruitless. Eventually, I utilized a pair of vise grips to squeeze the sections together, but they still would not snap into place. (If you have spare vise grips, they can live there forever...maybe) But it won't be weatherproof because  it's not connected.I plan to return this little monstrosity if I can possibly disassemble the assembled sections. If not, maybe I'll drive it over to Kohls as is and let Amazon worry about it.I know what you're thinking" "I'm handy—I can do it."That was my second mistake; the first was ordering it.

author: Terry
date: Reviewed in the United States on April 27, 2023
content: Read the reviews on this thinking ok, everyone has some issue with assembling this table.  Well turns out it does take some care when assembling, lining up the grooves at just the right ANGLE, then push to insert/lock into place.  The curves of each piece makes it a bit harder since you can't get a good steady grab of it to push into locking position.  But really, it still only took me no more than 20 minutes to put this together without using a heat/hair dryer as some recommended.  If you pay attention to angling/lining up the grooves just right and with a little pressure it snaps in.  It's sturdy considering it's all plastic material, just not sure if it would hold 300 lbs of weight if someone sat on it (I know it's not made for sitting).  In the end I think it's a bit pricey for what you get.  I'm keeping it though, since it's hard to find a round smaller outdoor table with storage at this point.

author: Ella Belle
date: Reviewed in the United States on September 17, 2024
content: I bought 2 of these YITAHOME 33 Gallon Round Deck Box, Outdoor Storage Box for Patio Furniture,Patio Table for Cushion, Pool Accessories, Waterproof Resin & Easy Assembly & Lightweight, Light Brown.I needed some rustic-looking storage bins with lids to use for storage AND for using as end tables!I picked the Light Brown color, as I figured it would be the easiest color to paint some details on later on so they will look more realistic.I had my husband assemble these, as I've had arthritis my entire life and can't use my hands very well.He assembled both of the YITAHOME 33 Gallon Round Deck Boxes with varying results.THE GOOD STUFF: - Both of the units arrived very well packaged and protected. - Both of the finished assembled Units look great and are just what I wanted. - Following the instructions  EXACTLY, the 1st Unit was pretty easy to assemble taking about 5 minutes after being unboxed. BUT, it did take some hand strength, which was why my Husband assembled these.THE NOT AS GOOD STUFF: - During assembly, it is very easy to pinch your fingers or clothing, OUCH! So be careful! - The 2nd Unit DID NOT go together as easily, BECAUSE Hubby DID NOT follow those instructions EXACTLY. - Hubby got side-tracked, then he THOUGHT he remembered how to assemble the 2nd unit! Oops! - This time, he went by the alphabetical order, (A, B, C, D) and NOT the INSTRUCTIONS order. - The INSTRUCTIONS ORDER MUST be followed EXACTLY, otherwise assembly problems WILL occur and you will have to disassemble and then reassemble. - DISASSEMBLY IS POSSABLE if done carefully. - To disassemble, you will need a flat-head screwdriver to push down on the tabs to do this! - It took Hubby around 45 minutes to disassemble and then reassemble that 2nd Unit!CONCLUSION: - The YITAHOME 33 Gallon Round Deck Box is a very nice looking, rustic style plastic storage Unit. - To save yourself a freakin' nightmare and a lot of time and frustration, follow those instructions! - AGAIN... IT IS VERY IMPORTANT TO FOLLOW THE INSTRUCTIONS EXACTLY! - I totally LOVE the finished product and I would order these again!

content: I was looking for something to put my accent pillows in on the deck but didn’t want the traditional deck box. I stumbled on this and it seemed the only negative was really the difficulty in assembly. I am really really good at putting things together so that wasn’t enough to discourage me. I received this today and went right to work. It started off solid, I even chuckled to myself this was a piece of cake! Enter step 6…. You basically snap together each half of the barrel and then step 6 is to put the two halves together. My chuckling quickly turned into frustration. This was no joke! There is nothing except solid muscle that’s going to help you get the two halves together! Other than that assembly is easy, and the final product is worth it. I may even consider a second one! Five stars for the final product.

author: Terry
date: Reviewed in the United States on April 27, 2023
content: Read the reviews on this thinking ok, everyone has some issue with assembling this table.  Well turns out it does take some care when assembling, lining up the grooves at just the right ANGLE, then push to insert/lock into place.  The curves of each piece makes it a bit harder since you can't get a good steady grab of it to push into locking position.  But really, it still only took me no more than 20 minutes to put this together without using a heat/hair dryer as some recommended.  If you pay attention to angling/lining up the grooves just right and with a little pressure it snaps in.  It's sturdy considering it's all plastic material, just not sure if it would hold 300 lbs of weight if someone sat on it (I know it's not made for sitting).  In the end I think it's a bit pricey for what you get.  I'm keeping it though, since it's hard to find a round smaller outdoor table with storage at this point.

author: ARVIN CASTRO
date: Reviewed in the United States on October 4, 2023
content: This is a great solution for those looking for deck storage that takes up little space, but still holds quite a lot of stuff.  In my case, I was looking for a solution that would hold all the accessories of my Solo Stove Bonfire, would serve as a “stand” to place the Bonfire on when it’s not in use and wouldn’t take up much space on my deck like the excellent Solo Stove Station would.  As you can see in my pictures, the internal storage is quite generous…it can hold not only the Solo Stove Shield, carrying handle and Sticks, but has more than enough room for the Heat Deflector and Grill/Griddle tops.  Once put together, the box is quite sturdy…placing my Bonfire with its Stand on top of it, I cannot feel any stress or “give”; it’s very stable and sturdy enough to hold much more weight-wise.  The lid is very solid and has a locking-lip design, so once in place, the box is easily sealed against the elements and offers the protection against the elements you would want for something that can stay on your deck throughout the year.The only negatives would be that assembly can be tricky…make sure you follow the instructions and assemble it in a warm environment as you could easily crack the plastic tabs/fittings if you force things too much.  Also, while not expensive, it is pricey for what is ultimately a plastic container that snaps together…there are no metal fittings, the lid isn’t attached and there’s no provision to lock the lid if you want to secure the contents inside.  Having said this, there aren’t that many choices for a round-design deck box solution that offers the internal volume and dimensions this thing does.Ultimately, this is a great choice for anyone looking for a solution that’s not your typical box shape (this is round), has a lot of storage capacity without taking up too much space, is sturdy enough to place heavy objects on and can keep your stuff protected all year long.  It even looks great!

author: Amy
date: Reviewed in the United Kingdom on September 5, 2024
content: Love the round storage but goodness me it was the most fiddliest thing I've ever put together and I've done some tough jobs.It takes a pair of big hands and a whole lot of manipulation to slot the pieces into each other, 5 interlinking slots along each edge, whilst one end goes in the other end pops out, turning them this way and that way just to get some kind of grip and the right angle to get the slippery pieces linked up.The ring at the bottom that holds the whole thing together at the end was the most difficult, almost as if it were too small.I had to wedge the whole thing up tight against the sofa with my feet up against it but whichever part I managed to attach another part would always pop off.I had to bang the ring down with my fist around it's circumference but it would still pop off somewhere else. I ended up sitting on the edge of the ring while pulling the body inwards to fit. I honestly thought I'd have to call someone in to hold it down for me.I bought two of these. The first one took me over half an hour to put together and the second took me twenty minutes and went smoother from practising on the first one. Nevertheless I have a very sore fist and I feel like the factory workers got out of doing the hardest part.Overall its good quality and very spacious inside, looks like it will hold over half of the contents of a rectangular trunk. It's really big, doesn't appear so because of the angle of the camera but it's almost double the size of the seat of the blue chair.Make sure you follow the instructions because if you go wrong it will be difficult if not impossible to unslot the parts without breaking them. Also don't panic when you see repeat letters for each of the pieces. There are A, B, C, D wrapped together, and then the same again wrapped separately. You have to put the four pieces together and repeat. Then you join the two halves together. That's the most awkward part along with the ring.

author: JMattingly
date: Reviewed in the United States on April 28, 2024
content: The reason I’m disappointed with this product is the poor manufacturing. The main issue I have is that the side panels do not line up correctly/completely with the back panels (see photos). I followed the instructions and slid both the side and back panels over in the bottom slots as far as they would go, but the panels do not fit together at the bottom on either left or right sides. On the left side of the unit the side panel is too far over on the back panel so the screw holes don’t line up. On the right side of the unit the side panel is too far away from the back panel so the screw holes don’t line up. I could only connect the back and side panels together at the top three spots but not the bottom three spots (with the lousy plastic screws provided), which makes the unit much less sturdy. It’s difficult to tell exactly what’s causing this—if it’s a problem with the slot placement on the bottom piece or if it’s something to do with the back and side panels. Regardless, the pieces simply do not fit together as they should.The other issue I had was that the screw holes were too small on the hinges that connect the front and top doors. I had to re-drill the holes on all hinges to get the screws to fit.For what I paid for this unit I expected much better quality.

author: The Young Homestead
date: Reviewed in the United States on July 18, 2024
content: We live in a rural, mountain town and have had all kinds of issues with our package deliveries. Our mailmen have left packages in all kinds of different places other than what one would think was the most obvious and easiest option: our front porch. Sometimes it's on the small retaining wall right across from the front porch (note said they couldn't figure out how to get to the porch...well how about you follow the obvious path, or just hop down the 2 feet from where you left the package and walk across to the porch...and then follow the path back to your truck?); and once, they literally opened the back door of a car in our driveway and put it in the backseat.  Not kidding. Image if that was a visiting friends' car!Our biggest battle was in getting them to stop leaving it directly against the basement French doors where 1) our son can't open to the doors to retrieve said packages, 2) it gets rained on due to no roof under the deck boards above it, and 3) time and time again isn't where we've asked them to put it!So in talking to our mail lady, she said to get a box and put it at our mailbox like other people do. Well, our mailbox is not in front of our rural homestead and we get a lot of larger shipments that require a huge box. Our mailbox is up the road on another road next to 3 other mailboxes and we don't want our packages up there where no one can see what's going on (no neighbors up there). So we decided to purchase this small "shed" and put signs on it (and in our mailbox) for oversized deliveries. So far, it's been a 75/25 delivery success in this box.  It's nice looking and easy for us and our delivery drivers to access.  It holds our largest packages and smaller ones. Very pleased with the purchase.

author: Tampadoc
date: Reviewed in the United States on May 31, 2023
content: After completing a garage floor epoxy project, I needed an outdoor storage shed to house some of my heavier tools and miscellaneous stuff that I no longer wanted to clutter the garage. I researched the available sheds (Rubbermaid, Suncast, Yitahome among others) and decided to get the Suncast. Unfortunately, Suncast does not ship to California. Ultimately, the Yitahome 27 cu ft shed fit my needs best so I placed the order with Amazon using a $20 off coupon.Number 1: You will likely receive two (2) separate deliveries, one with the sides and back panels as well as the hardware needed for assembly and the second package with the top and bottom sections. Both cartons had some tears and possible re-taping (jpg) but everything was A-OK and all of the pieces were included.Number 2: The instruction booklet and all of the hardware came in a single larger zip lock bag that was included with the side and back panels. The various screws, hinges and brackets were in separate smaller bags. Every single item was included and Yitahome provided some extra screws "just in case" (they actually list the numbers of each part to be used and note there are extras in some cases (example: 18 + 1 extra, 12 + 2 extra); very thoughtful service.Number 3: I did encounter some issues during assembly -  all of the panels are well marked and identified in the manual.  Unfortunately, one of the pieces (the left side panel),  would not slide into position no matter how hard I tried to get it to fit (jpgs).  I contacted Yitahome and Amazon on Monday, May 29, Memorial Day, and didn't expect a reply for days. However, Amazon did reach out promptly and offered to send new side panels. By that time, I had tilted the partially completed structure on its side and with the help of gravity, I guess, the left side panel slid into place. In all likelihood the panel needed to be lifted and slid in one motion (not shown in the manual or seen on the instruction video). So, having two people might make the assembly easier.Number 4: After that it was pretty straight forward. I'll reiterate, the instructions are well laid out with good illustrations and, with each part of the process, the manual shows you exactly which pieces are needed. Quite well done I must admit. There were a couple of issues of minor consequence: 1) there were no starter holes for the small metal piece that receives the metal roof arm support (jpg). I rectified this by applying firm pressure using an awl to create screw holes. 2) there was a film of resin (jpg) where a hinge was to be placed. Again, the awl allowed me to clear the obstruction and the hinge slid easily into place.Overall, the shed was easily assembled after fiddling with the reluctant left side panel and I would recommend it to anyone who needs a modest sized outdoor storage shed. If not for the issue with the side panel I would have given this 5 stars. Also, it has not been put through any sort of stress - weather is ideal today and it has only been in service for a few hours. I will update the review if there are changes but we won't get a serious rainfall for many months and the temperatures are seldom over 75ºF. Good luck with your purchase, whichever shed you choose. I do recommend the Yitamhome 27 cu ft outdoor shed.

author: JMattingly
date: Reviewed in the United States on April 28, 2024
content: The reason I’m disappointed with this product is the poor manufacturing. The main issue I have is that the side panels do not line up correctly/completely with the back panels (see photos). I followed the instructions and slid both the side and back panels over in the bottom slots as far as they would go, but the panels do not fit together at the bottom on either left or right sides. On the left side of the unit the side panel is too far over on the back panel so the screw holes don’t line up. On the right side of the unit the side panel is too far away from the back panel so the screw holes don’t line up. I could only connect the back and side panels together at the top three spots but not the bottom three spots (with the lousy plastic screws provided), which makes the unit much less sturdy. It’s difficult to tell exactly what’s causing this—if it’s a problem with the slot placement on the bottom piece or if it’s something to do with the back and side panels. Regardless, the pieces simply do not fit together as they should.The other issue I had was that the screw holes were too small on the hinges that connect the front and top doors. I had to re-drill the holes on all hinges to get the screws to fit.For what I paid for this unit I expected much better quality.

author: The Young Homestead
date: Reviewed in the United States on July 18, 2024
content: We live in a rural, mountain town and have had all kinds of issues with our package deliveries. Our mailmen have left packages in all kinds of different places other than what one would think was the most obvious and easiest option: our front porch. Sometimes it's on the small retaining wall right across from the front porch (note said they couldn't figure out how to get to the porch...well how about you follow the obvious path, or just hop down the 2 feet from where you left the package and walk across to the porch...and then follow the path back to your truck?); and once, they literally opened the back door of a car in our driveway and put it in the backseat.  Not kidding. Image if that was a visiting friends' car!Our biggest battle was in getting them to stop leaving it directly against the basement French doors where 1) our son can't open to the doors to retrieve said packages, 2) it gets rained on due to no roof under the deck boards above it, and 3) time and time again isn't where we've asked them to put it!So in talking to our mail lady, she said to get a box and put it at our mailbox like other people do. Well, our mailbox is not in front of our rural homestead and we get a lot of larger shipments that require a huge box. Our mailbox is up the road on another road next to 3 other mailboxes and we don't want our packages up there where no one can see what's going on (no neighbors up there). So we decided to purchase this small "shed" and put signs on it (and in our mailbox) for oversized deliveries. So far, it's been a 75/25 delivery success in this box.  It's nice looking and easy for us and our delivery drivers to access.  It holds our largest packages and smaller ones. Very pleased with the purchase.

author: Tampadoc
date: Reviewed in the United States on May 31, 2023
content: After completing a garage floor epoxy project, I needed an outdoor storage shed to house some of my heavier tools and miscellaneous stuff that I no longer wanted to clutter the garage. I researched the available sheds (Rubbermaid, Suncast, Yitahome among others) and decided to get the Suncast. Unfortunately, Suncast does not ship to California. Ultimately, the Yitahome 27 cu ft shed fit my needs best so I placed the order with Amazon using a $20 off coupon.Number 1: You will likely receive two (2) separate deliveries, one with the sides and back panels as well as the hardware needed for assembly and the second package with the top and bottom sections. Both cartons had some tears and possible re-taping (jpg) but everything was A-OK and all of the pieces were included.Number 2: The instruction booklet and all of the hardware came in a single larger zip lock bag that was included with the side and back panels. The various screws, hinges and brackets were in separate smaller bags. Every single item was included and Yitahome provided some extra screws "just in case" (they actually list the numbers of each part to be used and note there are extras in some cases (example: 18 + 1 extra, 12 + 2 extra); very thoughtful service.Number 3: I did encounter some issues during assembly -  all of the panels are well marked and identified in the manual.  Unfortunately, one of the pieces (the left side panel),  would not slide into position no matter how hard I tried to get it to fit (jpgs).  I contacted Yitahome and Amazon on Monday, May 29, Memorial Day, and didn't expect a reply for days. However, Amazon did reach out promptly and offered to send new side panels. By that time, I had tilted the partially completed structure on its side and with the help of gravity, I guess, the left side panel slid into place. In all likelihood the panel needed to be lifted and slid in one motion (not shown in the manual or seen on the instruction video). So, having two people might make the assembly easier.Number 4: After that it was pretty straight forward. I'll reiterate, the instructions are well laid out with good illustrations and, with each part of the process, the manual shows you exactly which pieces are needed. Quite well done I must admit. There were a couple of issues of minor consequence: 1) there were no starter holes for the small metal piece that receives the metal roof arm support (jpg). I rectified this by applying firm pressure using an awl to create screw holes. 2) there was a film of resin (jpg) where a hinge was to be placed. Again, the awl allowed me to clear the obstruction and the hinge slid easily into place.Overall, the shed was easily assembled after fiddling with the reluctant left side panel and I would recommend it to anyone who needs a modest sized outdoor storage shed. If not for the issue with the side panel I would have given this 5 stars. Also, it has not been put through any sort of stress - weather is ideal today and it has only been in service for a few hours. I will update the review if there are changes but we won't get a serious rainfall for many months and the temperatures are seldom over 75ºF. Good luck with your purchase, whichever shed you choose. I do recommend the Yitamhome 27 cu ft outdoor shed.

author: JMattingly
date: Reviewed in the United States on April 28, 2024
content: The reason I’m disappointed with this product is the poor manufacturing. The main issue I have is that the side panels do not line up correctly/completely with the back panels (see photos). I followed the instructions and slid both the side and back panels over in the bottom slots as far as they would go, but the panels do not fit together at the bottom on either left or right sides. On the left side of the unit the side panel is too far over on the back panel so the screw holes don’t line up. On the right side of the unit the side panel is too far away from the back panel so the screw holes don’t line up. I could only connect the back and side panels together at the top three spots but not the bottom three spots (with the lousy plastic screws provided), which makes the unit much less sturdy. It’s difficult to tell exactly what’s causing this—if it’s a problem with the slot placement on the bottom piece or if it’s something to do with the back and side panels. Regardless, the pieces simply do not fit together as they should.The other issue I had was that the screw holes were too small on the hinges that connect the front and top doors. I had to re-drill the holes on all hinges to get the screws to fit.For what I paid for this unit I expected much better quality.

author: The Young Homestead
date: Reviewed in the United States on July 18, 2024
content: We live in a rural, mountain town and have had all kinds of issues with our package deliveries. Our mailmen have left packages in all kinds of different places other than what one would think was the most obvious and easiest option: our front porch. Sometimes it's on the small retaining wall right across from the front porch (note said they couldn't figure out how to get to the porch...well how about you follow the obvious path, or just hop down the 2 feet from where you left the package and walk across to the porch...and then follow the path back to your truck?); and once, they literally opened the back door of a car in our driveway and put it in the backseat.  Not kidding. Image if that was a visiting friends' car!Our biggest battle was in getting them to stop leaving it directly against the basement French doors where 1) our son can't open to the doors to retrieve said packages, 2) it gets rained on due to no roof under the deck boards above it, and 3) time and time again isn't where we've asked them to put it!So in talking to our mail lady, she said to get a box and put it at our mailbox like other people do. Well, our mailbox is not in front of our rural homestead and we get a lot of larger shipments that require a huge box. Our mailbox is up the road on another road next to 3 other mailboxes and we don't want our packages up there where no one can see what's going on (no neighbors up there). So we decided to purchase this small "shed" and put signs on it (and in our mailbox) for oversized deliveries. So far, it's been a 75/25 delivery success in this box.  It's nice looking and easy for us and our delivery drivers to access.  It holds our largest packages and smaller ones. Very pleased with the purchase.

author: Tampadoc
date: Reviewed in the United States on May 31, 2023
content: After completing a garage floor epoxy project, I needed an outdoor storage shed to house some of my heavier tools and miscellaneous stuff that I no longer wanted to clutter the garage. I researched the available sheds (Rubbermaid, Suncast, Yitahome among others) and decided to get the Suncast. Unfortunately, Suncast does not ship to California. Ultimately, the Yitahome 27 cu ft shed fit my needs best so I placed the order with Amazon using a $20 off coupon.Number 1: You will likely receive two (2) separate deliveries, one with the sides and back panels as well as the hardware needed for assembly and the second package with the top and bottom sections. Both cartons had some tears and possible re-taping (jpg) but everything was A-OK and all of the pieces were included.Number 2: The instruction booklet and all of the hardware came in a single larger zip lock bag that was included with the side and back panels. The various screws, hinges and brackets were in separate smaller bags. Every single item was included and Yitahome provided some extra screws "just in case" (they actually list the numbers of each part to be used and note there are extras in some cases (example: 18 + 1 extra, 12 + 2 extra); very thoughtful service.Number 3: I did encounter some issues during assembly -  all of the panels are well marked and identified in the manual.  Unfortunately, one of the pieces (the left side panel),  would not slide into position no matter how hard I tried to get it to fit (jpgs).  I contacted Yitahome and Amazon on Monday, May 29, Memorial Day, and didn't expect a reply for days. However, Amazon did reach out promptly and offered to send new side panels. By that time, I had tilted the partially completed structure on its side and with the help of gravity, I guess, the left side panel slid into place. In all likelihood the panel needed to be lifted and slid in one motion (not shown in the manual or seen on the instruction video). So, having two people might make the assembly easier.Number 4: After that it was pretty straight forward. I'll reiterate, the instructions are well laid out with good illustrations and, with each part of the process, the manual shows you exactly which pieces are needed. Quite well done I must admit. There were a couple of issues of minor consequence: 1) there were no starter holes for the small metal piece that receives the metal roof arm support (jpg). I rectified this by applying firm pressure using an awl to create screw holes. 2) there was a film of resin (jpg) where a hinge was to be placed. Again, the awl allowed me to clear the obstruction and the hinge slid easily into place.Overall, the shed was easily assembled after fiddling with the reluctant left side panel and I would recommend it to anyone who needs a modest sized outdoor storage shed. If not for the issue with the side panel I would have given this 5 stars. Also, it has not been put through any sort of stress - weather is ideal today and it has only been in service for a few hours. I will update the review if there are changes but we won't get a serious rainfall for many months and the temperatures are seldom over 75ºF. Good luck with your purchase, whichever shed you choose. I do recommend the Yitamhome 27 cu ft outdoor shed.

author: JMattingly
date: Reviewed in the United States on April 28, 2024
content: The reason I’m disappointed with this product is the poor manufacturing. The main issue I have is that the side panels do not line up correctly/completely with the back panels (see photos). I followed the instructions and slid both the side and back panels over in the bottom slots as far as they would go, but the panels do not fit together at the bottom on either left or right sides. On the left side of the unit the side panel is too far over on the back panel so the screw holes don’t line up. On the right side of the unit the side panel is too far away from the back panel so the screw holes don’t line up. I could only connect the back and side panels together at the top three spots but not the bottom three spots (with the lousy plastic screws provided), which makes the unit much less sturdy. It’s difficult to tell exactly what’s causing this—if it’s a problem with the slot placement on the bottom piece or if it’s something to do with the back and side panels. Regardless, the pieces simply do not fit together as they should.The other issue I had was that the screw holes were too small on the hinges that connect the front and top doors. I had to re-drill the holes on all hinges to get the screws to fit.For what I paid for this unit I expected much better quality.

content: When I got this several months ago, I thought it was exactly what I was looking for - a storage box that was small enough to fit into the limited space I had available, but big enough to hold my gardening supplies and a bit extra.For the gardening supplies live shovels etc? author: Crystal Eldridge
date: Reviewed in the United States on May 7, 2023
content: I originally thought I had been sent an incorrect D panel due to the way the instruction manual is designed and just how different that panel looks to the rest of the box. The D panel feels a lot more flimsy, doesn't have the rattan look, and has different connectors than the other panels. Turns out, it's the bottom panel, and the giant, ugly D embossing  goes inside of the box. Once I figured that out the box went together pretty easily. Hopefully the box holds up, but the thinness of the bottom panel has me a bit concerned, so that and the manual are why I'm giving this three stars. The rest of it seems pretty sturdy and it's a good size. I'd already sent the company an email thinking I'd gotten the wrong back panel piece, so I sent a follow up and am adjusting my review here as well.

VERSATILE APPLICATION- This deck box has a 32-gallon capacity that provides ample room for daily indoor and outdoor storage of cushions, garden tools, etc.; Can also be used as a side table, patio seating, storage ottoman, or footstool.
EASY TO ASSEMBLE- Our outdoor storage box can be easily assembled with a LEGO-like KD(knocked-down) design; Only one person is required to put all panels together without any tools.
ALL-WEATHER GUARD- Weatherproof poly resin rattan combines beauty and utility, granting this patio deck storage protection against water, UV, fading, rusting, peeling, and bending; Requires little to no maintenance for years to come.
DESIGNED FOR CONVENIENCE- Our deck box has built-in handles on both sides for convenient lifting and movement; Add a combination lock/padlock (not included) to the top lid to offer extra security.
PRODUCT DIMENSIONS- With a 32-gallon storage capacity and dimensions of 22.1''L x 17.1''W x 20.9''H, this outdoor storage box is the optimal choice for storing small items with easy accessibility.

Recycled materials
Contains at least 95% recycled material.

author: Dwaine
date: Reviewed in the United States on June 8, 2023
content: Our old box started leaking and the pool towels were soaked and moldy so spent a lot of time looking for a new deck box. Wanted one smaller than old box and finally settled on this one. It is very flimsy and two  days after setting it outside we had a heavy rain/hail storm causing the lid to fly open and soaking the towels again. There is a small spot to latch it closed provided you can find something small enough to fit through the tiny holes and your fingers are small enough to work it open once in place. The only thing we had was the smallest lock made (like for a suitcase which fits through the end of the zipper). Terrible design and don’t expect it to hold up long. Would like to return it but that’s difficult once put together and the box it came in was destroyed. Gave it one star because it looks nice.

The only thing we had was the smallest lock made (like for a suitcase which fits through the end of the zipper). Terrible design and don’t expect it to hold up long. Would like to return it but that’s difficult once put together and the box it came in was destroyed. Gave it one star because it looks nice.

author: MRL

content: Shipping and packaging: Arrived on time, packaged well with no damage or issues.Assembly: When we initially thought we assembled this incorrectly, we had some trouble taking it apart again. The trick is to push a flathead screwdriver against the inside "tab", and have another person push against the joint to pop it out. It doesn't necessarily take a lot of brute force to do it, just the right angles based on how the locks are engineered. Other than our misunderstanding, this was very easy to assemble. You do have to really push to lock the pieces together. As others mentioned, use a rubber mallet if needed.Capacity: This fit 6 seat cushions (20x18 inches), 6 pillows (16x16 inches), a tabletop fire pit, a small plastic storage bin with some odds and ends, a large cover for our 6 person dining set (folded up small!), and a cover for our 11' umbrella. I put some very light items in the net - I wouldn't recommend anything heavy that will stretch it out.Durability/Design: I've noticed I have to pull the lid to the left a little to fully close it. I may need to adjust some of the items inside, or the hydraulic lift. I sat on it briefly and it seemed ok (150 lbs), but I don't plan to use it as a seat. I'm not sure the plastic could hold up to that pressure. I appreciate that you can add a lock to the lid. If it holds up well, I'd consider this a great value for the price.Weatherproof: I've only had it a few days, so can't comment on this yet.

The media could not be loaded.
                



***ANOTHER UPDATE 04/08/2024***Please do not buy this product.  So much money. I was so happy with it and then all the problems started. The lid had to be held down over the winter with bricks because the lid is so warped and leaks. The metal frame actually broke away from the warping.  Although the seller gave us a full refund I just do not feel good about people making the same mistake in buying this. We are looking for another one but are now so worried that we will have the same issues. So sad. This one will be thrown out 🥺***ANOTHER UPDATE 10/21/2023***I can not tell you how disappointed i was with this purchase.  I love this box.  It is perfect for our large deck and stores so much.  We had a problem with a leak in the lid and the company ended up reembursing us for the whole thing.  Ok, no problem.  We now have to drain the lid every time it rains.  Also with the heat of the summer the top buckled.  WELL this last weekend we were putting everything away from the deck when I noticed that the side of the lid was raised up quite a bit.  We raised it and started to look.  Not only was the top drooping from the heat, it actually pulled the metal frame away from the lid and it is not closing.  We stacked bricks on the top for now to keep the rain and evenually snow out of our stuff.  We live in Ohio.  We did not have a super hot summer.  People in much hotter states, this IS NOT FOR YOU.  So dissappointed**UPDATE**  SELLER MADE EVERYTHING RIGHT AND REIMBURSED US FOR THE DAMAGED PRODUCTWe originally really liked this but now we have problems with the lid being bowed and holding water.  No problem I just lift the lid and let the water fall down the back. The other day I noticed there is a hole inside the lid that is leaking all over my belongings inside. I can seal that up but why??  Where is the water getting in at. Then I have to leave the lid open to drain. This is going to get so nasty in the lid with the constantly sitting water

author: James
date: Reviewed in the United States on July 27, 2024
content: I had to order 3 of these in order to get 1 functional unit.  Amazon will not let me tell you about the problems with the first one.  The second one had a manufacturing defect.  I currently have unit number 3 and contacted the manufacturer to ask how to purchase an additional divider.  The unit will accommodate 2 dividers, but it only comes with 1.  The manufacturer was of no help whatsoever.  They wouldn’t even provide the part number of the divider.  All they would say is they don’t sell replacement parts.  That’s what you want to hear when you’ve just spent $350 on their product.  The unit has a lot plastic parts, which makes me skeptical of its durability and longevity.  I feel this one will go in the trash in a couple of years.  I wasn’t’ expecting it to be as flimsy as it is.  If kept indoors in a garage or basement, it might be ok, but I don’t see it surviving outdoors on a deck or patio.  UPDATE: Upon unpacking, a screw has already pulled loose from the lid.  As another reviewer stated, you’ll need to secure the metal frame for the lid with adhesive to prevent this from happening. .  I would look elsewhere.

author: BizyOwner
date: Reviewed in the United States on March 13, 2024
content: This review is for the item listed as, "YITAHOME 90 Gallon Large Deck Box, Double-Wall Resin Outdoor Storage Boxes, Deck Storage for Patio Furniture, Cushions, Pool Float, Garden Tools, Lockable & Waterproof (White)."I ordered a white one and got an ugly gray one. I had assigned the task  of unpacking and assembling it to two other people and did not know it was the wrong color until they came to me with assembly issues. The struts screw onto the lid with 4 screws in the backplate but two of the screw holes are directly behind the strut and cannot be accessed.  And the hinges are made of PLASTIC!The instructions are mostly pictures and are fantastic and easy to follow but they assigned numbers to everything but did not put numbers on anything so you are constantly flipping to the front of the manual to figure out what they are referring to. Now I have to decide between spending the time and money to paint this or taking it apart and hauling it to UPS for a return.  This took 10 minutes to unpack, another 10 to read the manual and figure out the parts, and another 20 to put it together. It came with a nice little screwdriver but we used the drill motor. There is one nut that needs a wrench. It is metric so we used the crescent wrench. The 20 minutes included time to get the tools. Had to jerry-rig a special tool to get to the screws behind the strut.

author: Andre Schwartz
date: Reviewed in the United States on May 24, 2023
content: I got one of these 230 gallon boxes to store pool floats. It's easy to assemble, but the lid didn't close well. After inspecting it, I found that the metal tubing that comes pre-installed in the lid was causing the problem. You can see this black metal tubing in  the advertisement photos. The pieces were cut too long to begin with and were then welded poorly which left an additional 1/8" or so gap. As a result, the metal frame doesn't properly fit in the channel in the molded plastic lid. Well that didn't stop them from cramming it into place and cracking the plastic. The minor crack isn't a big problem, but because the metal frame is out if square, it twists and warps the lid so it won't close properly. After a few weeks, the screws holding the frame to the lid started coming out. No surprise there. You can't attach a warped, ill-fitting metal frame to a piece of flimsy plastic with sheet metal screws and think it's gonna hold up.  I ended up removing the frame, cutting it to fit, drilling holes throuhg the lid and tubing, then bolting it to the top using some big flat washers so the screw heads wouldn't pull through the plastic. Giant PITA.

author: 421 DHC
date: Reviewed in the United States on August 3, 2023
content: The box is a good size, but there are some serious quality problems. Overall, it was a good size to fit pool toys, cushions, towels and an electric leaf blower w/ its cord. The box was a pain in the butt to assemble, but I got it done in a couple of hours. The lid was warped right off the bat, but it could still be closed and locked. i thought the warping might resolve itself once assembled. Nope. It just got worse. The warped lid is so bad now, exacerbated by the broken hinge/hydraulic attachment, that it can no longer be securely closed.Sadly, both rear joints have broken and are disconnected from the box lid. The lid is warped to the point that it won't shut now. I reached out to the manufacturer who NEVER responded and Amazon won't help. Crickets.I would NOT recommend this product (or anything else made by this manufacturer). Buy something else. I wasted $300 on a crap product.

author: Paul F.
date: Reviewed in the United States on April 6, 2024
content: Packaging needs to be addressed/improved. I had two delivered and both had minor damage. The delivery box is very large and fairly heavy so you can imagine how it can get dropped, etc. during shipping.Assembly: assembly design is simple and very easy to understand / follow instructions. Problem is that the pieces need to fit fairly precisely...and they don't. At least, on the two I assembled they didn't, and the problem was the same for both products. It's difficult to explain w/out a video or something, but suffice it to say, that if you get a similar product you need some muscle to get the panels to click together. The first one was a nightmare b/c I didn't know what the problem was. I actually ended up having to make some modifications (think power saw!) to get the panels to fit together. The second one was still an ever-loving b*tch, but I figured out a work-around much quicker (I flipped the panels/bottom over and using a 2x4 and mallet hammered the panels together - this was not wonderful but way better/less destructive than my first assembly.) I'm not a contractor but have build some furniture from scratch and put together plenty of pieces that just need assembly. This wasn't a clueless dude fumbling around. This was very difficult.Customer Service: the reason this was not 1 star is because I had a replacement unit shipped fairly quickly when I originally contacted them with the initial cracked (small crack) bottom panel. The person I spoke to was informed and the process was easy/quick. Because they shipped an entirely new unit instead of just a replacement for the damaged bottom panel, I got two of these for the price of one. The damage was minor and the first unit is fully functional, just not defect-free. The 2nd unit also had some damage on the corner of the top panel, but I have no need for another unit and honestly don't want to put another together.Hope this is helpful.

content: The Good: Easy Assembly. The Bad: The design of this box is to be cheap construction. The lid does not seat properly when closed. author: Teresita
date: Reviewed in the United States on August 11, 2023
content: This review is for the Yitahome xxl 230 gallon brown rattan deck box. Chose this because the xl size would fit the cushions from a new patio sofa. I was pleased when I saw the metal bar all along the lid. I thought it would keep the lid weighted and prevent warping, but I was wrong. In less than a week I saw that the lid had already warped. I don’t live in an extreme heat area. Pretty normal summer temperatures here and it wasn’t exposed to sun all day long.I contacted the company with pictures and explained the problem. Showed proof of purchase date. All they offered was $50. Said a replacement lid wasn’t possible. For the price of this, I would expect better quality of the product and customer support when their product fails. It’s no longer waterproof and a perfect entry point for insects. I haven’t heard back from them after I replied that their offer didn’t seem fair for this type of failure.I hope they’ll redesign the lid so their product won’t continue to fail for other customers. Very disappointed in this product. If the lid hadn’t failed, it would have been an attractive way to store the cushions and keep them protected from the weather. I don’t recommend purchasing this at all.

content: I really hate to leave a bad review because I know it really hurts the manufacturer but I also know for myself I count on reviews to help me decide about a product. Disappointing to spend so much on this and have it warp.

author: Lee M.
date: Reviewed in the United States on June 5, 2024
content: I bought the 230 gallon version of this as it was cheaper than the Keter and Suncast products we normally use. Ive assembled close to 30 of these at the resort I own. I am very competent at assembling chests like this.This unit is very poorly blow molded. The sides slide onto and clip in to the base. They 'snap' together. There was no way at all to get them to do this. The blow molding as uneven and had lips that prevented assemly. Only because I did not want to return it did I spend an hour messing with it. ultimately shaving down all the tabs (a very laborious process). The lid hinge doesn't line up and had to be twisted and contorted to get the screws in place. Some of the screws used by the manufacturer to hold metal supports in place (installed at the factory) were loose and cannot be tightened as the plastic is stripped.The front panel bows out slightly, so closing the lid has the lid catch go inside instead of outside the box, it also means the divider is loose.Steer well clear of this. Any money you might save is long gone on the extra work you'll put in to get it together. Even after all the assembly effort you'll be left with a saggy box that I suspect will last a year or two, rather than the 10 or more my other brand boxes are lasting.Note: I bought the 230 gallon. version. I have no idea if this is a universal problem across all sizes, but I won't be buying another to find out

author: Amazon Customer
date: Reviewed in the United States on April 12, 2024
content: Wasn't sure what to expect, but this was a pleasant surprise. Unit is well built and sturdy. Hasn't rained yet so I can't say for sure that it's waterproof, but the lid fits over the sides and there is no obvious way for it to leak. Unless you put it somewhere that it stands in more than an inch of water.Assembly is mostly very simple. The instructions are generally very good and everything fit perfectly. Two things could have been better. The instructions refer to the top/bottom and side panels by letter but the panels are not marked. The sides and top are obvious because of the screw holes for the hinges. The bottom is not. I had to guess which direction was the front, which is odd because the instructions make a point that it will only fit one way. The word "Inside" was molded into the top side of the bottom panel, so it would have been a simple matter for them to also mark "Front" or include an arrow or something. The front and back panels are each attached to one of the sides with a sort of hinge (just plastic that runs the width of the panel and folds). There are tabs in the front/back and sides that insert into the bottom and click into place. The first panel is easy because you can angle it to get the tabs to fully insert, but the rest have to be pushed in perpendicular and that proves a little difficult. They advise you to use a rubber mallet and that did help because you have to drive it in a bit and a steel hammer could damage the panels. I wound up using a wide putty knife tapped into the slot in the bottom to get the tab to fully insert, then used my body weight to push down and get it to snap into place. Worked fine.All in all, just a few minor things, none of which proved insurmountable. Again, very sturdy, and I would buy another product from this company at this point without hesitation.

author: Gail Douglas
date: Reviewed in the United States on April 28, 2024
content: We purchased the 150 gal white storage container. When I was unpacking the pieces and taking them back to my deck, I was happy with the double sided thickness. The panels were sturdy, and did not bow or warp at all as handled. So far so good. Got out the directions. They were total crap! Barely indicated what you had to do. Just basic pictures. But screws all fit, no hardware missing. Even included a cheap screwdriver. Now came the fun part. Under the cautionary statement on the first page, it says “align the holes before assembly and snap into place (the tabs) with a slight tap”. My hubby is a 44 year career engineer, and had issues. The directions say “note that the front and back of part D, which is the bottom piece, are different, so pay close attention during installation “. Well, the piece is clearly marked “inside “ but we could tell no difference at all in the front or back edge. We finally took a shot and lined it up so you could read the word “inside” as you would open the lid. We guessed correctly! Then, we started tapping the tabs into the slots . Well, we tried. A couple popped right in, but with way more than a “slight tap”. After cracking a couple tabs, we stepped back and looked over the situation because I was aggravated that the tabs were breaking. At my suggestion, we flipped the box over, and tried tapping in the tabs from the BOTTOM of the box! Worked perfectly! No more broken ones. I was so miffed that I would have sent it back at this point, except we damaged it assembling, and those good ‘ole directions say that “once installed, the product cannot be detached”. Oh, great. So all in all, we have a very sturdy box, assembled, with some cracked tabs that don’t seem to be much of an issue, yet, that looks very nice. But they absolutely have to do something about improving the directions, like adding WRITTEN instructions and tips on better assembly procedures! I despise following assembly to the letter and damaging the product in the process! Ridiculous For what we paid!

author: Rhonda Freshwater
date: Reviewed in the United States on February 5, 2024
content: I purchased this box to store my crabbing gear and camping stuff at my lot on the coast. Almost 11 months later, I have noticed (like others) that the top has become warped and some of the screws have pulled away from the lid on one corner. I think a lot of it has to do with it being in the direct sun all day and the drastic weather we've had this past year in Louisiana — first extremely hot then freezing. Even with the warping, I see no signs of water intrusion. I am going to do what one of the other reviewers suggested and add 4" hook & eye closures to the corners to prevent further warping and possibly try some longer screws to replace the ones that have pulled out. Customer service was very responsive and offered a partial refund.

author: Steve Yates
date: Reviewed in the United States on July 28, 2024
content: The product came undamaged and in good condition.  Instructions are just pics but were easy to follow, hardest part is making sure you grab the correct screws for each step.  Its so easy to assembly you'll want to try without the instructions until you grab the wrong hardware and it doesn't fit.I found the product to be rugged and mostly well constructed (see below).  When fully assembled, it seems very strong.  I can easily get on the top without it buckling under the weight.  The walls seem sturdy and do not flex and bow out like many single wall storage containers.  My main concern for the future is if the corners become brittle and break due to UV.Assembly was very easy, except for the hinge insert nuts in the top.  They are poorly attached and will come out easily.  I plan on removing them all and epoxying them in to hold better.Only other negative comment is that there is a small gap where the sides are attached.  When you put the sides together an push them tight, the gap disappears, but comes back when you put in all the screws.  I can see where water could get inside in a driving rain, so I put silicone caulk at these joints, as well as the joints at the floor.  There are also small gaps around the lift supports that mice could enter, so I had to seal these.Overall, I am very pleased with the results and would recommend this product.  For the money spent and time consumed vs building my own, it is a bargain.

date: Reviewed in the United States on August 2, 2024
content: We had ordered two of these boxes during Prime day.  The first one went together nicely and we were happy with the quality.  The lid is a soft open/close lid so that was nice as well.  On the second box, however, the metal frame of the lid was not square on the left side.  Because of this the three holes on the bracket for the hydraulic shock would not line up and could not be attached to the lid.  I emailed Yitahome to see if they could send us a replacement lid and offered to ship the defective lid back.  They simply offered to send us an entire new complete deck box and said we could keep the other one also!!!  What a great company.  I'm not sure what we're going to do with this other box though. author: Amazon Customer
date: Reviewed in the United States on October 1, 2023
content: There is a major defect.  The 'snap' system is designed incorrectly.  The walls have to be leaned in and then pulled back for the inserts to go into the hole well enough to snap in.  You cannot just push down.  This is problematic in 2 ways.  First, the front long wall and short side wall are hinged together.  you can snap in the front wall but then you can not snap in the side wall because you cannot lean it forward.  Second, because you have to slide the second long wall and side wall down hinges on wall one, you cannot lean either piece in to snap.  This is the 2nd Yitahome 260 gallon deck box we have ordered.  We had the same problem with the first one but were hoping that was a defect as the box is really of high quality.  Both are inside a shed so they are still usable for our purpose but they could not be used outdoors.

author: DogBoy
date: Reviewed in the United States on January 28, 2024
content: Overall, I'm neutral about this product. It's a little complicated for one person (and I'm an engineer) to put together as in some situations during assembly, you need three hands. My biggest complaint is that the 90-gallon storage adequately holds my eight patio cushions with some degree of stuffing, but adequately. The problem arises when I try to close the lid; the plastic front wall/siding is too soft and bows under stress, not allowing the lid to latch. For a fix, I purchased from HD a 2' threaded rod, drilled through the plastic walls, and ran it front-to-back, somewhat stiffening the bow-effect and correcting the issue.

author: Gail Douglas
date: Reviewed in the United States on April 28, 2024
content: We purchased the 150 gal white storage container. When I was unpacking the pieces and taking them back to my deck, I was happy with the double sided thickness. The panels were sturdy, and did not bow or warp at all as handled. So far so good. Got out the directions. They were total crap! Barely indicated what you had to do. Just basic pictures. But screws all fit, no hardware missing. Even included a cheap screwdriver. Now came the fun part. Under the cautionary statement on the first page, it says “align the holes before assembly and snap into place (the tabs) with a slight tap”. My hubby is a 44 year career engineer, and had issues. The directions say “note that the front and back of part D, which is the bottom piece, are different, so pay close attention during installation “. Well, the piece is clearly marked “inside “ but we could tell no difference at all in the front or back edge. We finally took a shot and lined it up so you could read the word “inside” as you would open the lid. We guessed correctly! Then, we started tapping the tabs into the slots . Well, we tried. A couple popped right in, but with way more than a “slight tap”. After cracking a couple tabs, we stepped back and looked over the situation because I was aggravated that the tabs were breaking. At my suggestion, we flipped the box over, and tried tapping in the tabs from the BOTTOM of the box! Worked perfectly! No more broken ones. I was so miffed that I would have sent it back at this point, except we damaged it assembling, and those good ‘ole directions say that “once installed, the product cannot be detached”. Oh, great. So all in all, we have a very sturdy box, assembled, with some cracked tabs that don’t seem to be much of an issue, yet, that looks very nice. But they absolutely have to do something about improving the directions, like adding WRITTEN instructions and tips on better assembly procedures! I despise following assembly to the letter and damaging the product in the process! Ridiculous For what we paid!
